---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="CV · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="Curriculum vitae of Xiaochuan Li — M.Sc. Human and AI at the University of Technology Nuremberg, working on language, reasoning, and AI."
>
  <header class="mb-10">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-medium tracking-tight">Xiaochuan Li</h1>
      <a href="/cv.pdf" class="no-print text-sm text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline whitespace-nowrap">Download PDF ↗</a>
    </div>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1">
      M.Sc. Human and AI · University of Technology Nuremberg
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] mt-2">
      <a href="mailto:xiaochuan.li@utn.de" class="hover:text-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors">xiaochuan.li@utn.de</a>
      · <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li" class="hover:text-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors">github.com/xchuan-li</a>
      · Nürnberg, Germany
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Education</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 break-inside-avoid">
        <div>
          <p class="font-medium">M.Sc., Human and AI</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">University of Technology Nuremberg (UTN)</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1">Focus (formal semantics of modality): do language models possess rich modal representations — possibility and necessity as quantification over a space of alternative worlds, in the line from Kripke through Kratzer to Leahy &amp; Carey — and when in training do modal distinctions emerge? Tested with causal-inference rigor (controlled interventions that dissociate modal words from modal bases, negative controls) across typologically diverse languages, rather than large-scale circuit discovery.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">2025 — 2027</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 break-inside-avoid">
        <div>
          <p class="font-medium">German language program</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">University of Marburg · intensive German for graduate study</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">2024 — 2025</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 break-inside-avoid">
        <div>
          <p class="font-medium">B.A., Philosophy</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Shenzhen University · College of Humanities</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1">
            Senior thesis: <a href="/writing/from-leibniz" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline"><em>On Leibniz's Logical Theory</em></a> (advisor: Zang Yong)
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1">
            Coursework: logic, history of philosophy, analytic philosophy, mathematical logic; electives in cognitive psychology and linguistics. This background shapes my focus on reasons, causality, and what makes an inference licensed.
          </p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">2020 — 2024</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Papers &amp; planned outputs</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm">
      <li class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <span class="font-medium">Stable Is Not Grounded</span>
          <span class="text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">workshop paper · in submission</span>
        </div>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-0.5">Binary certification for whether the licensing structure is load-bearing — the piece written for publication (BlackboxNLP target).</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/sc-certification" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
          <span class="text-[var(--color-text-dim)]"> · </span>
          <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li/stable_is_not_grounded" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">GitHub ↗</a>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <span class="font-medium">Isotrace</span>
          <span class="text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">decision experiment · horizon</span>
        </div>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-0.5">Behavioral path localization via path-encoded fictional names — a design-stage horizon that upgrades binary certification into hop-level diagnosis; runs as a go/no-go on whether it separates genuine multi-hop reasoning from shortcut-copying, and becomes a paper if it does.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/isotrace" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Projects</h2>
    <div class="space-y-5">
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">Arrowhead</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">personal · pilot complete</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm mt-1">A completed mechanistic pilot on a real LLM (Gemma-2-2B). Linear probes, activation steering, and layer-band ablation show the model holds a representation of causal direction — which event is the cause — that is linearly decodable (cross-domain peak ≈ 0.94), causally efficacious under steering, and abstract enough to transfer to fictional, zero-frequency relations, yet redundantly distributed across layers (ablation cannot cleanly remove it). End-to-end interpretability pipeline designed, run, and analyzed on an HPC GPU cluster.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1.5">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/arrowhead" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">HanGL — surface Hangul, latent Hanja</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">collaborative</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm mt-1">The structure-versus-surface question run on real LLMs through a natural phenomenon: Korean Sino-Korean words, where Hangul shares no characters with its Hanja origin yet matches it in meaning. A wrong-Hanja intervention shows latent grounding scales with model capability — strong models neither need the cue nor are misled by it; a weak one is both. Pilot complete; scaling up.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1.5">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/hangl" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
          <span class="text-[var(--color-text-dim)]"> · </span>
          <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li/HanGL" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">GitHub ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">Latent Control States</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">collaborative</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm mt-1">Does prompt framing — urgency, authority, epistemic positioning — only change an LLM's outputs, or shift a causally relevant latent state? A controlled two-agent data pipeline is built; linear probing and activation patching come next. A collaborative project carried out with, and advised by, a senior researcher at DFKI (the German Research Center for Artificial Intelligence).</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1.5">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/latent-control-states" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">Cross-lingual ProtoBias</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">collaborative</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm mt-1">An applied multimodal stress test: does a vision-language model track semantic content, or language- and culture-specific prototype shortcuts? Extends a forthcoming paper from an established NLP research group with a cross-lingual evaluation, now at its second iteration.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1.5">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/cross-lingual-protobias" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
          <span class="text-[var(--color-text-dim)]"> · </span>
          <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li/cross_lingual_protobias" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">GitHub ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">MiniCausalLang</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">personal · workbench</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm mt-1">A language-to-causal-graph workbench that makes grammatical structure, the inference it licenses, and interventions on it observable — the shared substrate the certify / localize / quantify methods are built and tested on.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1.5">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/mini-causal-models" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Skills</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic mb-4 max-w-prose">
      Consolidating the technical stack my research program needs — controlled linguistic data
      generation, transformer-based model evaluation, intervention-based causal testing, and
      reproducible experiment pipelines.
    </p>
    <div class="space-y-3 text-sm">
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">Programming &amp; data</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Python (NumPy, pandas, scikit-learn), Git, LaTeX.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">ML / NLP tooling</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Building working proficiency with PyTorch and HuggingFace Transformers — model inference, dataset pipelines, and LoRA fine-tuning.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">Causal &amp; interpretability methods</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Controlled do-interventions, causal graphs, and shortcut-severing audits; developing behavioral path-tracing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">Linguistic evaluation</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Designing controlled stimuli for morphology, agreement, dependency structure, and word order — drawing on grammar-sensitive work across Chinese, German, English, and Japanese.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Languages</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Mandarin Chinese (native) · German (C1) · English (C1) — spanning isolating, fusional, and analytic types. Learning Japanese, to extend the range with an agglutinative, head-final system — the typological span my linguistic work draws on.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Interests</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed">
      Formal semantics of modality in language models (Leibniz → Kripke → Kratzer → Leahy &amp;
      Carey): whether LMs develop rich modal representations, when modal distinctions emerge in
      training, and whether the acquisition trajectory resembles human development. Method:
      controlled linguistic interventions across typologically diverse languages, dissociating modal
      words from modal bases (可能/必须/一定 vs. <em>may/must</em> vs. <em>können/müssen/dürfen</em>),
      with causal-inference rigor as the lens. The boundary between behavioral and mechanistic
      certification. Philosophy of measurement and of language in ML. World-model approaches (LeCun,
      Pearl) and the limits of pure-LLM paradigms.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
